		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/26/world/asia/26-rajnath-IndiaInk/26-rajnath-IndiaInk-tmagArticle-v3.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/26/world/asia/26-rajnath-IndiaInk/26-rajnath-IndiaInk-tmagArticle-v3.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/26/world/asia/26-rajnath-IndiaInk/26-rajnath-IndiaInk-tmagArticle-v3.jpg" id="100000002902495" width="592" height="439" alt="Rajnath Singh, president of the Bharatiya Janata Party, took oath as a cabinet minister in the new government on Monday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="439"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Rajnath Singh, president of the Bharatiya Janata Party, took oath as a cabinet minister in the new government on Monday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sam Panthaky/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/27/after-the-inauguration-ministers-roles-announced/" data-title="After the Inauguration, Ministers&#8217; Roles Announced" data-description="The morning after Mr. Modi&#039;s inauguration as India&#039;s next prime minister, the government announced portfolios for 45 ministers. Here are a look at some top cabinet appointments.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><br />
NEW DELHI &#8212; After Narendra Modi was sworn in as Indiaâs next prime minister, his new cabinet ministers took the oath of office.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While the outgoing prime minister, Manmohan Singh, had a team consisting of more than 70 ministers, Mr. Modiâs team was made up of a leaner 45 ministers, including cabinet ministers, ministers with independent charge and ministers of state. The leaner look is in tune with Mr. Modiâs mantra of &#8220;less government and more governance.&#8221; </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Tuesday morning, the government released the final <a href="//pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=105163">list</a> of who will oversee key ministries. Apart from being prime minister, Mr. Modi will oversee the departments of space and atomic energy. Here are the leaders of other key ministries.<span id="more-76262"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Home Ministry</strong> âRajnath Singh, the president of the Bharatiya Janata Party, will lead the ministry that oversees internal security and the police forces. There has been <a href="//www.business-standard.com/article/politics/rajnath-singh-appears-set-to-be-the-next-home-minister-114052500634_1.html">speculation</a> in the local media that the internal security part of the post would be placed under the control of the prime minister, part of a strengthening of the office that Mr. Modi is reported to want. Mr. Singh, 63, won election to Parliament from Lucknow, Uttar Pradesh, and is a former chief minister of the state as well as a union minister of agriculture in the last B.J.P.-led government. Mr. Singh is considered to be a <a href="//indiatoday.intoday.in/story/rajnath-singh-narendra-modi-pm-swearing-in-2014/1/363623.html">close confidante</a> of Mr. Modi.Â  Mr. Singh is also <a href="//www.bjp.org/leadership/shri-rajnath-singh">closely associated</a> with Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh, the Hindu right-wing organization that mobilized for the party during the campaign.<br />
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/27/world/asia/27-jaitley-IndiaInk/27-jaitley-IndiaInk-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/27/world/asia/27-jaitley-IndiaInk/27-jaitley-IndiaInk-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/27/world/asia/27-jaitley-IndiaInk/27-jaitley-IndiaInk-blog480.jpg" id="100000002903422" width="480" height="345" alt="Arun Jaitley, a senior leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party, taking oath as a cabinet minister in New Delhi on Monday. Mr. Jaitley would be handling both finance and defense ministries."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="345"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Arun Jaitley, a senior leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party, taking oath as a cabinet minister in New Delhi on Monday. Mr. Jaitley would be handling both finance and defense ministries.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Adnan Abidi/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Finance, Corporate Affairs and Defense</strong>Â â Arun Jaitley, who lost in the parliamentary elections in Amritsar, was widely <a href="//in.reuters.com/article/2014/05/26/india-politics-cabinet-jaitley-modi-idINKBN0E60BN20140526">seen as the front-runner</a> for the Finance Ministry so the head of defense is a bit of a surprise. Though India has been the <a href="//www.economist.com/news/briefing/21574458-india-poised-become-one-four-largest-military-powers-world-end">largest importer of arms</a> in the past five years, some of its recent weapons deals have been <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/02/16/business/global/india-takes-step-to-pull-contract-from-italian-helicopter-maker.html">plagued</a> by corruption scandals. Indiaâs armed forces have engaged in major skirmishes with enemy troops over borders with China and Pakistan in the past year and Mr. Modi <a href="//www.firstpost.com/politics/live-bjps-pm-candidate-narendra-modi-addresses-rally-in-rewari-1110095.html">has repeatedly called</a> for a tougher stance on the countryâs borders.  A corporate lawyer, for the past five years Mr. Jaitley had served as the opposition leader in the upper house of Parliament. Mr. Jaitley served as union minister of commerce and industry as well as law and justice in the previous B.J.P.-led government. He would likely be the minister to execute Mr. Modiâs vision for the economy, the revitalization of which is seen as a key reason for the B.J.P.âs election victory.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/26/world/asia/26-swaraj-IndiaInk/26-swaraj-IndiaInk-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/26/world/asia/26-swaraj-IndiaInk/26-swaraj-IndiaInk-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/26/world/asia/26-swaraj-IndiaInk/26-swaraj-IndiaInk-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000002902494" width="480" height="360" alt="Sushma Swaraj, left, a senior leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party, with Narendra Modi, India&#039;s prime minister, in New Delhi on May 17."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="360"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Sushma Swaraj, left, a senior leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party, with Narendra Modi, India's prime minister, in New Delhi on May 17.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Raveendran/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>External Affairs</strong> Â â Sushma Swaraj was the former leader of opposition in the lower house of Parliament and a senior leader of the party.Â  She is known to be jingoistic when neighbors have threatened India.Â  After an Indian soldier was found beheaded in January at the Line of Control that divides Kashmir, Ms. Swaraj <a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/09/26/ahead-of-india-pakistan-talks-12-killed-after-militant-attacks-in-jammu/">called</a> for the Indian Army to behead 10 Pakistani soldiers in response.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Throughout the campaign, Mr. Modi spoke frequently about India&#8217;s â<a href="//www.deccanchronicle.com/140508/nation-current-affairs/article/election-commission-working-under-pressure-narendra-modi">weak foreign policy</a>â and pledged to make the country a more muscular presence in international affairs. Ms. Swaraj, 62, has held cabinet posts of information, broadcasting and communications as well as health and family welfare in the previous BJP-led government under Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee. </p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/27/world/asia/27-gadkari-IndiaInk/27-gadkari-IndiaInk-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/27/world/asia/27-gadkari-IndiaInk/27-gadkari-IndiaInk-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/27/world/asia/27-gadkari-IndiaInk/27-gadkari-IndiaInk-blog480.jpg" id="100000002903416" width="480" height="310" alt="Nitin Gadkari, right, took oath as a cabinet minister in charge of the ministry of transport at the Rashtrapati Bhavan in New Delhi on Monday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="310"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Nitin Gadkari, right, took oath as a cabinet minister in charge of the ministry of transport at the Rashtrapati Bhavan in New Delhi on Monday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Adnan Abidi/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Transport</strong> â Although the previous government had set up separate ministries to handle departments like shipping and surface transport, this government has decided to consolidate road transport, highways and shipping under one minister, Nitin Gadkari. Mr. Gadkari, 56, who hails from Nagpur in Maharashtra, served as a public works minister in the B.J.P.-Shiv Sena state government in the late 1990s. Mr. Gadkari has faced corruption allegations related to Purti Group, a company he founded. Last year, he was forced to step down from the B.J.P. presidentâs post after the Income Tax authorities raided several of the companyâs offices for <a href="//indiatoday.intoday.in/story/nitin-gadkari-income-tax-raids-bjp-presidential-elections-congress/1/247204.html">alleged evasion of taxes</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The list released on Tuesday morning confirmed that no cabinet posts would go to older leaders like L.K. Advani and Murli Manohar Joshi, both of whom are in their 80s and are regarded as two of the founding members of the party.</p>
	</div>
